---

<Layout title="Tablespoon to mL: Accurate Medicine Dosing" description="Tablespoon to mL for accurate medicine dosing. Why kitchen spoons are unreliable and how to measure doses correctly." keywords="tablespoon to ml, medicine dosing, teaspoon ml, liquid medicine, accurate dosing, medicine measurement, tablespoon conversion">
  <div class="max-w-3xl">
    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose">
        <a href="/blog" class="hover:text-amber-600">Blog</a> <span class="mx-1">›</span> <span class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">Cooking</span>
      </nav>
      <BlogCrossLinks title="Tablespoon to mL: Accurate Medicine Dosing" />
      <p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8">June 30, 2025 • 4 min read</p>

      <p>Many liquid medicines still list doses in tablespoons or teaspoons, but using actual kitchen spoons can lead to significant over- or under-dosing. Here is what you need to know about accurate measurement.</p>

      <h2>The Standard Conversions</h2>
      <div class="bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl p-5 my-6 not-prose">
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400">1 tablespoon (tbsp) = 15 mL</p>
        <p class="text-center text-lg font-mono font-bold text-amber-700 dark:text-amber-400 mt-1">1 teaspoon (tsp) = 5 mL</p>
        <p class="text-center text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-2">1 tablespoon = 3 teaspoons</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Why Kitchen Spoons Are Dangerous for Medicine</h2>
      <p>Research has shown that household spoons are unreliable for dosing medicine:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Kitchen tablespoons vary from 6 mL to 29 mL depending on the spoon</li>
        <li>Teaspoons range from 2 mL to 9 mL — nearly double the intended dose at the high end</li>
        <li>A 2016 study found that 70% of parents made dosing errors when using kitchen spoons</li>
        <li>The American Academy of Pediatrics recommends only using mL-marked syringes or cups</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Safe Dosing Tools</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Oral syringe:</strong> Most accurate (±0.5 mL), best for children and precise doses</li>
        <li><strong>Dosing cup:</strong> Good for adults, read at eye level on a flat surface</li>
        <li><strong>Dropper:</strong> For very small doses (infants), usually marked in mL</li>
        <li><strong>Medicine spoon:</strong> Calibrated spoon with mL markings — better than kitchen spoons but less accurate than syringes</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Common Medicine Doses Converted</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>1/2 teaspoon = 2.5 mL (common infant dose)</li>
        <li>1 teaspoon = 5 mL (common children's dose)</li>
        <li>2 teaspoons = 10 mL</li>
        <li>1 tablespoon = 15 mL (common adult dose for cough syrup)</li>
        <li>2 tablespoons = 30 mL (1 fluid ounce)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Tips for Accurate Dosing</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Always use the measuring device that comes with the medicine</strong> — it is calibrated for that specific product</li>
        <li><strong>Ask your pharmacist</strong> for an oral syringe if the medicine does not include one</li>
        <li><strong>Think in mL</strong> — if a doctor says "one teaspoon," confirm whether they mean exactly 5 mL</li>
        <li><strong>For children:</strong> doses are usually calculated by weight (mg per kg), so get the exact mL amount from your pharmacist</li>
        <li><strong>Never use abbreviations loosely</strong> — "tsp" and "tbsp" look similar and a mix-up means a 3x dosing error</li>
      </ul>

      <p>When in doubt, always measure in millilitres. It is unambiguous, internationally understood, and the safest way to dose liquid medications accurately.</p>

      <div class="border-t border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-800 mt-10 pt-8 not-prose">
        <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-4">Try It Now</h3>
        <a href="/convert/cooking" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 rounded-lg bg-amber-500 text-white text-sm font-semibold hover:bg-amber-600 transition-colors">Open Cooking Converter →</a>
      </div>
    
      <div class="not-prose mt-8 p-4 bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 border border-amber-200 dark:border-amber-800 rounded-xl">
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 font-medium">🔗 Try our converter: <a href="/convert/cooking" class="text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 font-bold hover:underline">Open Converter →</a></p>
      </div>
    </article>
  </div>
</Layout>
